@node U_Usage "Usage"

  @{FG Shine}How to use Update@{FG Text}
  =================

  This tool is quite easy to use. All you have to do is this:

  1) Get yourself a TIC processor that has a special execute command
     if it gets a TIC file with a MAGIC field in it. A good one is
     CrashTick, which can be found on Aminet in comm/fido. The latest
     version is v1.1.

  2) Copy Update to somewhere in you path. I have it placed in Mail:bin,
     where I store all my Fidonet executables.

  3) Now you have to put in a row in the TIC processor so that it will
     execute Update when it gets a new MAGIC filename. In CrashTick you
     just start CrashTickPrefs, press Commands and in the string gadget
     called Magic command you write the following.

     Mail:bin/Update <configfile> %m %n <magic string>

     where configfile is the path including filename to the config file
     of your filerequest program, %m is the magic name of the file
     (CrashTick uses %m as a % code for the magic name. Change this
     if your TIC processor uses another % code for it), %n is the
     filename including path to the file (this is a CrashTick specific
     % code, change to suit your program). The magic string is optional.
     It will tell the program how the new row in the config file will
     look. The default is "MAGIC %m %n", which is the format GoldFreq (my
     filerequest program) use. Make sure the MAGIC keyword is in upper
     case, or otherwise Update wont find it when it have to update it.

     If you e.g. use FFRS then you should use the following string:

     "MAGIC name %%m file %%n"

     Please note the double % chars! This is because that is needed to get a %
     char in the string when it has passed through CrashTick.
     These % codes is _NOT_ the same as the one CrashTick uses, this is
     Updates own % codes. %m or %M inserts the magic name, %n or %N inserts
     the filename in the MAGIC string.

     Don't forget to enclose the MAGIC string with quotes.

     Now all you have to do is use the program. Whenever you get new TIC files
     which has a MAGIC field in it, your TIC processor will start Update, and
     Update will update/add the MAGIC field to the config file for your
     filerequest server program.

     One important thing though: Since the C function strstr() think upper and
     lower case chars are different, you have to convert all your MAGIC keywords
     to uppercase in order to get Update to update old magic names.

  I've added a lot of error checking, so that your old config file wont be lost or
  trashed. As it is now, I name the new config file <configfile>.new, and if everything
  goes well, and the config file is written without errors, it will delete the old
  configfile and rename the <configfile>.new to <configfile>. If anything goes wrong,
  it will delete the <configfile>.new and exit with an error code.
@endnode

@node U_CLI "CLI options"

  @{FG Shine}The CLI options@{FG Text}
  ===============

  Update <configfile> <magicname> <filename> [magic string]

  <configfile> is the config file, including path, to your Fidonet
  filerequest server program. This can be the config file of GoldFreq,
  FFRS or any other freq server program. Convert all MAGIC keywords in
  it to upper case before you use Update, or otherwise Update will miss
  updating those magic names and instead add a new MAGIC keyword for it.

  <magicname> is the magic name of the incoming file. This name will be
  the one that is in the TIC file. Your TIC processor must be able to
  send this field on to Update, or otherwise this will not work. If you
  use CrashTick, then all you have to do is enter %m for this one.

  <filename> is the filename, including path, to the magic file. If you
  use CrashTick, use %n here.

  [magic string] is an optional string (default is "MAGIC %m %n") that
  tells Update how the new MAGIC line will look like. Note that the %
  codes here isn't the same as the one above. These are the % codes that
  Update use. %m or %M is for the magic name and %n or %N is for the filename.
  If you use GoldFreq, this line will look like this (please note the
  double % chars. This is to get a % char after it has passed through
  CrashTick. If you only enter one % char CrashTick will think it's a
  % code that it should translate, and that's not what you want):

  "MAGIC %%m %%n"

  which is the default string. For FFRS it will look like this:

  "MAGIC name %%m file %%n"

  If your filerequest program writes it in antoher format, then change it
  to suit your program. Please note that the MAGIC keyword must be in all
  UPPER case chars!
@endnode

@node U_Future "Future"
  
  @{FG Shine}Some info about Update and the future@{FG Text}
  =====================================
  
  Well, there isn't much more to do... Maybe I'll add some more examples
